Introduction¶

The NBA, is the best Basketball association in the whole world, and though it started in America the league over the year continued to expand globally. Today the international fan base plays a big role for the NBA and each year they try to expand even more, for example by having some games played in different countries around the world. The goal of our project is to come up with an interpretable model to predict the amount of international viewers a game may have. We retrieved our data directly from the NBA and some of the features were scraped online, which will be discussed more in depth later on. Below is a list of features for each factor:

  • Temporal
    • Game Date
    • Month
    • Day of Week
  • Player and game data
    • Total All Stars in Game
    • Team Success
    • Late Game Score Difference
    • Total International Players in Game
    • Total Final Score
    • Total time-outs taken
  • Social media impact
    • Twitter Followers
  • Team value
    • Forbe's Annual Team Valuation

In our project we explored different features of the four factors listed above. Our goal was to construct a model to predict the number of international viewers per game. We analyzed the features above before implementing them into the model to get insight on the results of the predictive model and better understand the trends in the features.

Data sets¶

We were given four datasets from the NBA listed below:

  • Game Data
  • Player Data
  • Training Data
  • Test data

All of these data sets range contain data pertaining to the 2016-2017 and 2017-2018 NBA season. Additionally, all these data sets are all linked through the common column of game_id Besides the data sets that were given to us we had to web scrape data for team value, social media, and additional game data which will be discussed in late section.

Training and Test data¶

The training and test data include the same information. Both contain information on how many international viewers a game had from each individual country. These countries are not identified but are rather given an ID so there is no way to really analyze viewership by a specific country. When analyzing a features effect on international viewership we used the training data set as it has information on more game than the testing data set. We used the testing data set to measure how good our predictive model is. Below is a couple rows from the training data set.

Assumptions made¶

Since our main data came directly from the NBA, we did not need to clean any data and all of the features were the appropriate type. The only thing we were unable to figure out was the units of the rounded viewers which is present in the training and testing data set. T However, this does not have any affect on our analysis as the units of the "rounded viewers" column will not change any pattern or trend this feature may have with other features.

1 Temporal Impact on International Viewership¶

1.1 Methodology¶

We would like to see if viewership numbers do change over certain periods, which would be an indication that would lead us to believe there is an association between time (seasonal/temporal) and viewership. Here we will explore how average international viewership persists over game dates, months, and day of week over the two seasons from 2016-2018.

1.3 Findings¶

In reference to the graph of the average viewership by game dates, most of the games tend to average 10,000 to 30,000 international viewers per game. Looking closer at the 2016-2017 season, we can see from the graphs that early in the season the international viewership is at its highest, but that over time the international viewership drops steadily.

There are multiple unique game dates were the average international viewership is unusually high. Other than the first few games of the season, there are some other dates that spike unusually high. One date where international viewership numbers increase significantly in both the 2016-2017 and 2017-2018 season is December 25, which is Christmas. Upon further research, we discovered that these games are hand-picked by the NBA, in recent years games that were played on December 25 include a rematch of the NBA Finals.

From the graph of viewership numbers by game date, we can see an overall negative trend, but this trend is made clearer when looking at how viewership changes over the months. Also, games on thursdays average the most viewers.

Source

  • Why Christmas Day is special in NBA https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Basketball_Association_Christmas_games

2 Social media impact¶

2.1 Twitter followership¶

2.1.1 Methodology¶

To explore this factor, we first scraped the official NBA team twitter accounts to get their respective follower counts and then used team performance data, specifally using the game ID, rounded viewers, and away/home teams features to get the average viewership for each team. We then combined this with the corresponding team's number of twitter followers to see if there is any correlation.

2.1.2 Analysis¶

# Scrape the number of followers from each NBA account and store in data.csv
with open('data.csv','w') as file:
    filewriter = csv.writer(file, delimiter=',', quotechar='|', quoting=csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL)
    filewriter.writerow(['Team', 'Number of Followers'])

    for handle in teams:
        temp = requests.get('https://twitter.com/'+handle)
        bs = BeautifulSoup(temp.text,'lxml')
    
        try:
            follow_box = bs.find('li',{'class':'ProfileNav-item ProfileNav-item--followers'})
            followers = follow_box.find('a').find('span',{'class':'ProfileNav-value'})
            numFollows = followers.get('data-count') 
            
        except:
            print('Account name not found...')
        
        filewriter.writerow([handle, numFollows])

file.close()

# This function finds the average number of views for a team
def find_avg_views(team):
    '''Takes a team and computes the average number of views'''
    
    total_view = 0
    length = 0
    for idx,value in enumerate(list(sum_views["teams_in_game"])):
        if team in value[0]:
            total_view += list(sum_views["Rounded Viewers"])[idx]
            length += 1

    average_views = total_view / length
    return [team, average_views]

team_avg_views = [find_avg_views(team) for team in teams]

2.1.3 Findings¶

From the visualization, we can see the points that stand out the most are the Miama Heats, the Chicago Bulls, the Golden State Warriors, and the Cleveland Cavaliers.

The data generally supports our hypothesis since most of the teams who had low twitter followership also had low viewership and the Golden State Warriors exemplified the case of high twitter followership with high viewership. However, the two outliers, the Chicago Bulls and the Miami Heats, had high followership but low viewership, which we believe is atttributed to past successes that may have garnered a lot of popularity and fans that aren't representative of current popularity, and thus, current viewership.

3 Team Value¶

3.1 Forbe's annual team valuation¶

3.1.1 Methodology¶

Every year Forbes announces its annual valuations of the National Basketball Associations 30 teams. Factors that influnce the value of the team include soaring local media deals, new arenas and basketballs international popularity. Here we are interested in determining if there is a corrsespondence in the features of team values defined by Forbes Current Value on international viewership. We hypothesize that increased team value will result in higher average viewership per game Revenues and operating income are for the NBA season and net of revenue sharing and arena debt service. Team values are enterprise values (equity plus net debt) of team based on current arena deal (unless new arena pending).

3.1.2 Analysis¶

In [17]:
# We will begin by webscraping the team valuations from the Forbes website.
def get_data(soup):
    
    # extract desired text from element
    team = soup.select_one("body > div.main-content.main-content--universal-header > main > div > div > div.gallery-wrap > div.gallery-content > div.gallery-slider > div > fbs-carousel > div.fbs-slider__slides-wrapper > div > div.fbs-slider__slide.ratio4x3.active.primary > div.gallery__slide-content > div > div.flex-container > h1").text
    texts = soup.select("body > div.main-content.main-content--universal-header > main > div > div > div.gallery-wrap > div.gallery-content > div.gallery-slider > div > fbs-carousel > div.fbs-slider__slides-wrapper > div > div.fbs-slider__slide.ratio4x3.active.primary > div.gallery__slide-content > div > div.col-md-9.gallery__slide-caption p")
    current_value = texts[1].text.strip() # path for current_value
    revenue = texts[2].text.strip() # path for revenue
    operating_income = texts[3].text.strip() # path for operating income

    data = {
        "Current value" : current_value,
        "Revenue" : revenue,
        "Operating income" : operating_income,
        "Team" : team
        }
    
    return data

# first page
url = "https://www.forbes.com/pictures/mli45fhhid/1-new-york-knicks/#7a902d0d48ae"

# set up chrome webdriver
driver = webdriver.Chrome("chromedriver") # need to install driver and give path
driver.get(url)
python_button = driver.find_element_by_css_selector("body > div.main-content.main-content--universal-header > main > div > div > div.gallery-wrap > div.gallery-content > div.gallery-slider > div > fbs-carousel > div.fbs-slider__controls > button.fbs-slider__control-right")

# colletion of all team data
datalist = []
teams_scraped = []

# obtain all 30 NBA team market value data
while len(datalist) < 30:
    
    # Selenium hands page to Beautiful soup
    soup = BeautifulSoup(driver.page_source, "html.parser")
    
    # obtain data for this image
    data = get_data(soup)

    # add this teams data to data collection
    if data["Team"] not in teams_scraped:
        time.sleep(3)
        datalist.append(data)
        teams_scraped.append(data["Team"])

    # get next image
    try:
        python_button.click()
    except:
        time.sleep(3) # give page more time to render
        python_button.click()
        
    time.sleep(3)

# We will create some helper functions to convert the data types of the columns we wish to use.
def convert_to_monetary(value, containsBillions = False):
    '''Takes a a string value representating a value from the "Current value", "Operating income", or "Revenue column"
    and extracts the numerical value converts it into appropriate data type. containsBillions refers to if column has values
    in the billions, if so then the unit for the column will be billions. Otherwise it will be millions.'''
    
    isNegative = False
    # check for negative values
    if "-" in value:
        isNegative = True  
    
    # convert a billion value
    new_value = None
    if "bil" in value:
        new_value = value.split("$")[1].strip()
        new_value = float(new_value.split()[0])
    
    # convert a million to billion
    else:
        new_value = value.split("$")[1].strip()
        new_value = float(new_value.split()[0])
        if containsBillions: 
            new_value = new_value / 1000
        
    if isNegative:
        new_value = "-" + str(new_value)
        new_value = float(new_value)
        
    return new_value

def convert_to_name(name):
    '''Takes a team name and ranking and just extracts the team name'''
    
    new_name = None
    new_value = name.split(".")[1].strip()
    
    return new_value

# Convert the column data types
market_df["Current value"] = [convert_to_monetary(value, containsBillions = True) for value in market_df["Current value"]] # current value
market_df["Team"] = [convert_to_name(team) for team in market_df["Team"]] # team name

4 Player and game data¶

One of the factors we were primarily interested was in player and game data. Alot of features for this factors were given, but not all of them were important. We looked at many features to see how they relate to international viewership in the NBA. Some of these features included: number of all-stars in the game, the winning percentage of the team, how close the game is in the fourth quarter and finally how many international players there are in a game.

4.1 Number of all-stars¶

In the NBA each season, there is an all star game which is a game between the best players from the western conference and the best players from the eastern conference.

4.1.1 Methodology¶

To investigate this feature, we first found the total amount of all-stars who played per game id from the player data set. Then we combined that with data on the total amount of viewers per game acquired from the training data set.

4.1.2 Analysis¶

4.2 Team record¶

In this section, we will observe the viewership numbers relative to how successful a team is doing (i.e.- high win percentages). Not necessarily to explore the idea of a "band-wagon" fan, but we aim to see if international viewers are actually interested in watching better teams or if viewership is independent of team success.

4.2.1 Methodolgy¶

To explore this feature, first we calculated the winning percentage per team using the data from the game data. To make sure our results are accurate we only looked at the winning percentages of teams that have played atleast 20 games. After doing that we merged that data to the total amount of viewers per game through their shared column of game_id. We then assigned the following labels to the winning percentages:

  • greater than 75% : Top
  • less than 75% and greater than 50% : Upper-Mid
  • less than 50% and greater than > 25% : Lower-Mid
  • less than 25%: Bottom

Next, to check the relationship among the amount of international viewers and winning percetange we looked at the team with highest winning percentage per game.

4.2.2 Analysis¶

In [28]:

# Assigning a label based off the winning percentage 
def label(win_rate):
    '''Takes a win_rate and applies the appropriate label describing their win percentage.'''
    return np.where(win_rate >= 0.75, '75% <= win-rate',
                    (np.where(win_rate < 0.75 and win_rate > 0.50 , '50% < win-rate < 75%',
                              (np.where(win_rate > 0.25, '25% < win-rate < 50%', 'win-rate < 25%')))))

# create new column with the labels for each winning percentage
games["win_rate_label"] = games["win_rate"].apply(label)
win_rec = games[games.win_rate.notnull()].reset_index()

4.3 Closeness of the game¶

We were interested in seeing if the international audience of the NBA tends to watch an NBA game if its a close game. As fans of the NBA, we predict that the closer the game is the more viewers that game will have.

4.3.1 Methodology¶

So to explore this feature from the game data we looked at point deficit in the last two minutes. In the game data we were given the last two minute score for each of the two teams per game. Given that we were able to compute the point deficit in the last two minutes for each game.

4.3.2 Analysis¶

In [31]:
def get_dif(num):
    ''' The function takes in a game id and computes last 2 min point deficit for that game'''
    x = game_dat[game_dat["Game_ID"] == num].reset_index()
    dif = abs(x["L2M_Score"][0] - x["L2M_Score"][1])
    return dif
In [32]:
# Gets the l2m point deficit

ptd_dat = pd.DataFrame(new_dat.groupby("Game_ID")["ptd"].max())
ptd_vs_views = tot_view_dat.join(ptd_dat)

4.6 Total Time outs¶

We were interested in investigating the relationship among total timeouts in a game taken and the international viewership for that game. We hypothesisze that there will be a negative relationship, because we felt as if a game uses more timeouts it will reduce the amount of followers or cause them to change the channel.

4.6.1 Methodology¶

In order to investigate this feature we took the sum of full and short timeouts per team for each game id. We then merged it with the data on total rounded viewers per game id to perform further analysis

4.6.2 Analysis¶

In [35]:
games = game_dat.copy()
Full_Timeouts1 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Full_Timeouts"].max() # full timeouts for team one
Full_Timeouts2 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Full_Timeouts"].min() # full timeouts for team two (may be same as other team)
Short_Timeouts1 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Short_Timeouts"].max() # short timeouts for team one
Short_Timeouts2 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Short_Timeouts"].min() # short timeouts for team two (may be same as other team)]

5 Predictive Model¶

Now that we explored various features in depth that we believed would influence international viewership. Next we will use some of these features to construct a linear regression model to predict future international viewership.

Features implemented into model

  • Total Final Score
  • Total All Stars in Game
  • Avg Views Per Game by Date
  • Combined Wins Entering Game
  • Highest Scorer in Game
  • Total Timeouts Called

5.1 Features¶

def get_avg_viewership_per_game_for_unique_date(game_date):
    '''Takes a game_date string and finds the corresponding average viewership per game for that date, by indexing
    the "avg_views_by_date" Series'''
    return avg_views_by_date[game_date]

Full_Timeouts = pd.DataFrame(Full_Timeouts1 + Full_Timeouts2) # total full timeouts for that game
Short_Timeouts = pd.DataFrame(Short_Timeouts1 + Short_Timeouts2) # total full timeouts for that game
Total_Timeouts = pd.DataFrame(Full_Timeouts["Full_Timeouts"] + Short_Timeouts["Short_Timeouts"]) # sum timeouts for ea. game
tot_timeouts = Total_Timeouts.reset_index().rename(index=str, columns={0:"total_timeouts"})
data = pd.merge(data, tot_timeouts, on=['Game_ID'], how = 'left')

# Feature 4: Max Scorer in Game
highest_scorer = pd.DataFrame(players.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Points"].max().reset_index()) # highest scorer for each game
data = pd.merge(data, highest_scorer, on=['Game_ID'], how = 'left')

# Feature 5: Wins Entering Game
# can just take highest team because most will probably look to be watching the better team
wins_entering_game1 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Wins_Entering_Gm"].max().reset_index()["Wins_Entering_Gm"]
wins_entering_game2 = games.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Wins_Entering_Gm"].min().reset_index()["Wins_Entering_Gm"]
wins_entering_game = wins_entering_game1 + wins_entering_game2
id_and_wins_entering_game = pd.DataFrame({"Game_ID":games.groupby("Game_ID").max().reset_index()["Game_ID"],"wins_entering_game":wins_entering_game})
id_and_wins_entering_game.head(1)
data = pd.merge(data, id_and_wins_entering_game, on=['Game_ID'], how = 'left')
# can just take highest team because most will probably look to be watching the better team
games["Game_Date"] = pd.to_datetime(games["Game_Date"]) # convert to date
# ignore first 40 games of season
start_date = '2016-12-01'
end_date = '2017-4-13'
season1 = games[(games["Game_Date"] > start_date) & (games["Game_Date"] < end_date)]
wins_entering_game = season1.groupby(["Game_ID"])["Wins_Entering_Gm"].max().reset_index()["Wins_Entering_Gm"]
id_and_wins_entering_game = pd.DataFrame({"Game_ID":season1.groupby("Game_ID").max().reset_index()["Game_ID"],"wins_entering_game_2":wins_entering_game})
data = pd.merge(data, id_and_wins_entering_game, on=['Game_ID'], how = 'left')

# Feature 6: Number of all-stars
all_stars = players[players["ASG_Team"] != "None"]
all_stars = all_stars[all_stars["Active_Status"] == "Active"]

       'Avg Views Per Game by Date', 'Combined Wins Entering Game',
       'Highest Scorer in Game', 'Total Timeouts Called']]

## Evaluating the Model
from sklearn import metrics

print('MAE:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
print('R-squared: ', metrics.explained_variance_score(y_test,predictions)) # R^2

# check residuals distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.distplot((y_test-predictions));

The coefficients tells us if we hold all others features fixed a 1 unit increase in that feature is associated with an increase of the coefficient value. From this we know that the number of all stars in a game is associated with the greatest increase of viewers when all other features are fixed.

To validate the assumptions of our predictive model we checked the distribution of the residuals. Since we got that the distribution is approximately normal, we can confidently say that the linear regression model was an appropriate model for the data.

After creating a linear regression model to predict international viewership, we were able to able an average predicted error of about 4100. Considering the fact that was apparent in prior visualizations, the average error we obtained is not so bad, since the average viewership per game can range anywhere from 1,000 viewers to over 80,000 viewers.
